item.title: Hollywood players back Black Lives Matter
item.description: Netflix, Amazon, Hulu, HBO and other major Hollywood players are using their social media accounts to support the Black Lives Matter movement amid protests over the death of George Floyd at the hands of police officers.

item.title: PM sets virtual summit with India’s Modi
item.description: Prime Minister Scott Morrison will be holding a a "Virtual Summit" with his Indian counterpart Narendra Modi on Thursday.

item.title: Qld pubs’ staff restrictions ‘too costly’
item.description: A Queensland Health plan to heavily curb wait staff movements will have such a financial impost on pubs they will not open despite the easing of restrictions, says an industry body.

item.title: Rio apologises for WA heritage destruction
item.description: Mining giant Rio Tinto has apologised to traditional owners in Western Australia's north after destroying a significant indigenous site dating back 46,000 years, saying it is urgently reviewing plans for other sites in the area.

item.title: Understanding the legality of sex work
Israel kills unarmed autistic Palestinian
item.description: Israeli police have shot dead an unarmed autistic Palestinian man in Jerusalem's Old City after saying they suspected he was carrying a weapon.

item.title: Spacex launches humans into space
item.description: SpaceX founder Elon Musk says he was "overcome with emotion" after NASA astronauts Robert Behnken and Douglas Hurley launched into space.

item.title: US governors call in National Guard
item.description: Governors in several US states have called in National Guard troops as protests over police killings of black men intensifies.

item.title: Trump’s new threat to protesters
item.description: US President Donald Trump has sent a stark warning to people protesting the death of George Floyd, announcing the military was “ready, willing and able” to be deployed to Minnesota.

item.title: UK at ‘dangerous moment’ in pandemic
item.description: Britain is facing a "very dangerous moment" with the easing of lockdown restrictions, the deputy chief medical officer says after a growing number of experts questioned the relaxation of rules.
